00:47:52.320 --> 00:47:54.120
Can you explain that story?

00:47:54.120 --> 00:47:54.930
PAUL ENGLISH: Yeah.

00:47:54.930 --> 00:47:58.595
Actually, why don't you
describe that story.

00:47:58.595 --> 00:47:59.604
Yeah.

00:47:59.604 --> 00:48:01.770
Because I was sort of manic
at the time, and I think

00:48:01.770 --> 00:48:04.145
Tracy was sane at the time.

00:48:04.145 --> 00:48:05.270
TRACY KIDDER: More or less.

00:48:05.270 --> 00:48:06.910
More or less.

00:48:06.910 --> 00:48:12.410
Well, as I recall,
there was a notice

00:48:12.410 --> 00:48:15.360
of a lighthouse up for auction.

00:48:15.360 --> 00:48:18.600
It was the most seaward
lighthouse in Boston Harbor.

00:48:18.600 --> 00:48:21.720
That is right out in the
ocean on a pile of rocks

00:48:21.720 --> 00:48:23.550
called Grave's Ledges.

00:48:23.550 --> 00:48:27.210
Paul loves parties
and he wanted to make

00:48:27.210 --> 00:48:30.150
a new kind of party place.

00:48:30.150 --> 00:48:31.250
I saw the e-mails.

00:48:31.250 --> 00:48:34.242
Anyway, the description
of the lighthouse

00:48:34.242 --> 00:48:35.700
wasn't all that
encouraging though,

00:48:35.700 --> 00:48:40.020
because it had no
plumbing, no electricity.

00:48:40.020 --> 00:48:42.780
And to get to it,
which was really

00:48:42.780 --> 00:48:45.330
unsafe to do in calm weather,
but to get to it-- to get

00:48:45.330 --> 00:48:49.890
into the lighthouse, you had to
climb on a ladder 30 feet long.

00:48:49.890 --> 00:48:52.410
And I was kind of
interested to imagine

00:48:52.410 --> 00:48:53.800
the people in
their party clothes

00:48:53.800 --> 00:48:58.410
looking down at
these crashing waves.

00:48:58.410 --> 00:49:03.330
The next day, Paul awoke and
thought, what have I done?

00:49:03.330 --> 00:49:06.000
That's the stupidest
thing I've ever done.

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:12.480
But I guess hypermania is not
entirely unusual in Boston

00:49:12.480 --> 00:49:15.102
because someone bid
more for the lighthouse

00:49:15.102 --> 00:49:16.537
and got him off the hook.

00:49:21.120 --> 00:49:25.250
Most of Paul's fits of hypomania
were as harmless as that.

00:49:25.250 --> 00:49:30.690
When I mentioned that story to
Brenda, your significant other,

00:49:30.690 --> 00:49:34.212
she just laughed for about
five minutes and she said,

00:49:34.212 --> 00:49:35.580
it's nothing.

00:49:35.580 --> 00:49:36.780
What harm did that do?

00:49:36.780 --> 00:49:40.615
Something good would
have come out of it.

00:49:40.615 --> 00:49:42.780
I don't know.

00:49:42.780 --> 00:49:48.330
I must say, hypomania is a
fascinating phenomenon to me.

00:49:48.330 --> 00:49:50.850
I did some research on it
and I spoke to a great expert

00:49:50.850 --> 00:49:54.570
on it-- and a
clinician researcher,

00:49:54.570 --> 00:49:58.920
and I said, somehow I
can't quite explain it.

00:49:58.920 --> 00:50:03.720
I kind of know when this guy is
about ti-- when this thing is

00:50:03.720 --> 00:50:05.910
beginning to take over.

00:50:05.910 --> 00:50:08.695
And he said, well,
that's perceptive of you.

00:50:08.695 --> 00:50:10.320
I don't think I know
any clinicians who

00:50:10.320 --> 00:50:13.920
deal with people who are subject
to hypomania, who wouldn't

00:50:13.920 --> 00:50:16.440
tell you that it's contagious.

00:50:16.440 --> 00:50:18.150
They would say it
was contagious,

00:50:18.150 --> 00:50:19.990
in the sense that you feel it.

00:50:19.990 --> 00:50:22.980
I think of a guitar
string being plucked

00:50:22.980 --> 00:50:27.200
and the other instruments
sounding board, vibrating.

00:50:27.200 --> 00:50:30.060
A sense for me of things
coming just a little too fast--

00:50:30.060 --> 00:50:34.200
and the story I've
told which it seems

00:50:34.200 --> 00:50:36.930
innocuous, but these
winter days-- I

00:50:36.930 --> 00:50:39.592
remember these winter days
where Paul was off at a meeting.

00:50:39.592 --> 00:50:41.050
He had about 10
meetings every day.

00:50:41.050 --> 00:50:46.920
But get to a restaurant,
get our coats hung up,

00:50:46.920 --> 00:50:47.890
everything's going OK.

00:50:47.890 --> 00:50:51.270
And Paul says something and
I want to write it down,

00:50:51.270 --> 00:50:55.730
and I write this down,
because I like to take notes.

00:50:55.730 --> 00:50:58.320
And I look up and
suddenly somehow he's

00:50:58.320 --> 00:50:59.312
in his winter coat.

00:50:59.312 --> 00:51:01.020
And he's standing
there and he's smiling.

00:51:01.020 --> 00:51:05.210
And he's saying very
pleasantly, ready to go?

00:51:05.210 --> 00:51:08.125
It's just the way I think of it.

00:51:10.249 --> 00:51:11.040
PAUL ENGLISH: Yeah.

00:51:11.040 --> 00:51:13.330
The hypomanic stuff
I think has been

00:51:13.330 --> 00:51:15.880
a contributor to my success.

00:51:15.880 --> 00:51:18.280
Bipolar has the
downs and the ups.

00:51:18.280 --> 00:51:23.210
And the downs for me were near
crippling when I was in my 20s.

00:51:23.210 --> 00:51:26.400
I would spend a lot
of time housebound

00:51:26.400 --> 00:51:28.490
and on the floor of my bedroom.

00:51:28.490 --> 00:51:30.470
I couldn't even sleep on a bed.

00:51:30.470 --> 00:51:32.800
It's hard to explain
why that was the case.

00:51:32.800 --> 00:51:35.800
And luckily at some
point, I discovered

00:51:35.800 --> 00:51:39.220
a med that works really
well for me for the downs.

00:51:39.220 --> 00:51:40.780
I used to have
panic attacks a lot.

00:51:40.780 --> 00:51:43.990
But I haven't experienced
any of the real downs

00:51:43.990 --> 00:51:47.650
or panic attacks for
more than 10 years now.

00:51:47.650 --> 00:51:50.240
But on the ups, the
tricky thing about it

00:51:50.240 --> 00:51:53.510
is the meds that
I will get to work

00:51:53.510 --> 00:51:56.720
for me, after about
a year on a new med,

00:51:56.720 --> 00:52:00.290
my visualization of what happens
is the brain finally figures

00:52:00.290 --> 00:52:03.970
out how to work its way around
the med and rewires itself.

00:52:03.970 --> 00:52:05.140
And the med no longer works.

00:52:05.140 --> 00:52:06.220
Then you begin this cross.

00:52:06.220 --> 00:52:08.719
But the problem is when you go
through a manic phases, which

00:52:08.719 --> 00:52:12.340
for me, last weeks at a
time, sometimes months,

00:52:12.340 --> 00:52:14.390
it feels really, really good.

00:52:14.390 --> 00:52:16.030
It feels very electrifying.

00:52:16.030 --> 00:52:18.430
Like I can feel it in
my arms all the time.

00:52:18.430 --> 00:52:27.610
And the problem with being manic
or hypomanic is left untreated,

00:52:27.610 --> 00:52:29.550
you can do really stupid things.

00:52:29.550 --> 00:52:32.350
And you're filled with
grandiosity and your mind

00:52:32.350 --> 00:52:33.970
races.

00:52:33.970 --> 00:52:37.760
People become really slow
and I have this perception

00:52:37.760 --> 00:52:40.700
when I'm manic, that other
people just can't understand me

00:52:40.700 --> 00:52:42.800
and they can't keep
up with me, which

00:52:42.800 --> 00:52:45.550
I know is just the grandiosity
speaking when I'm saying--

00:52:45.550 --> 00:52:49.870
and I pursue with vigor lots
of crazy different ideas

00:52:49.870 --> 00:52:52.640
all the time.

00:52:52.640 --> 00:52:56.180
And there's other downsides
of being manic as well.

00:52:56.180 --> 00:52:59.830
I write large checks.

00:52:59.830 --> 00:53:05.720
I hook up with people I
shouldn't be hooking up with.

00:53:05.720 --> 00:53:08.300
There's a lot of things I do
when I'm totally manic that I

00:53:08.300 --> 00:53:10.180
then end up later regretting.

00:53:10.180 --> 00:53:12.130
But I think overall,
it's been really

00:53:12.130 --> 00:53:15.590
useful as an entrepreneur to
have these weeks at a time

00:53:15.590 --> 00:53:19.300
if not months of
this crazy energy.

00:53:19.300 --> 00:53:21.680
SPEAKER 1: Do you have
like totems or things

00:53:21.680 --> 00:53:23.470
you use to like
